Why this works

  • nodes and edges are lists of free-form maps you can add any properties React Flow adds later (style, className, hidden, etc.) without backend changes.

  • connectorFlow.metadata can hold flow-level configs (layout, zoom level, etc.).

  • Everything stays JSON-friendly MongoDB can store directly.

You didnt annotate nodes, edges, and metadata with @Field.

Why it still works without @Field

  • By default, Spring Data MongoDB maps Java property names to MongoDB document keys as-is.

  • So nodes "nodes", edges "edges", metadata "metadata".

  • Thats why you see the correct JSON in Mongo even without @Field.

When to use @Field

You only need @Field("custom_name") if:

  • You want the MongoDB field name to be different from your Java property name.

  • Or you want more control (e.g., using snake_case in Mongo while keeping camelCase in Java).

Example:

java
@Data
public static class ConnectorFlow implements Serializable {
    @Field("nodes")
    private List<Map<String, Object>> nodes;

    @Field("edges")
    private List<Map<String, Object>> edges;

    @Field("metadata")
    private Map<String, Object> metadata;
}

This is optional since the names match anyway.

TL;DR: You dont need @Field for nodes and edges unless you want to rename them in Mongo.
If youre fine with the same field names, leaving it without @Field is perfectly correct.

Perfect consistency matters a lot when youre going to query and maintain these flows later.

Best Practices for Naming in MongoDB

  1. Choose one convention and stick with it (across all collections and fields).

  2. MongoDB doesnt enforce a schema, but consistent naming makes querying much easier.

  3. Industry standard for MongoDB is usually snake_case for field names (matches JSON style better).

Suggested Naming Convention

  • Collection name plural, snake_case

    • Example: connector_flow_data (you already did this right).

  • Field names in documents snake_case

    • Example: created_by, last_edited_by, connector_flow.

  • Nested structures also snake_case for consistency.

    • nodes, edges, position.x, position.y, community_id, community_type.

java
package com.italent.iconnector.xcommunitymongo.model;

import java.io.Serializable;
import java.util.Date;
import java.util.List;
import java.util.Map;
import java.util.UUID;

import org.springframework.data.annotation.Id;
import org.springframework.data.annotation.LastModifiedDate;
import org.springframework.data.annotation.ReadOnlyProperty;
import org.springframework.data.mongodb.core.index.Indexed;
import org.springframework.data.mongodb.core.mapping.Document;
import org.springframework.data.mongodb.core.mapping.DocumentReference;
import org.springframework.data.mongodb.core.mapping.Field;

import com.fasterxml.jackson.annotation.JsonIgnore;
import com.fasterxml.jackson.annotation.JsonIgnoreProperties;
import com.italent.iconnector.common.model.ConnectorMapping;

import lombok.Data;

@Document(collection = "connector_flow_data")
@JsonIgnoreProperties(ignoreUnknown = true)
@Data
public class ConnectorFlowData implements Serializable {

    private static final long serialVersionUID = -5857831216854849031L;

    @Id
    @Field("flow_id")
    private String flowId = UUID.randomUUID().toString();

    @DocumentReference(lazy = true, collection = "connector_mappings",
            lookup = "{ '_id' : ?#{#self.connector_mapping_id} }")
    @ReadOnlyProperty
    @JsonIgnore
    private ConnectorMapping connectorMapping;

    @Field("name")
    @Indexed
    private String name;

    @Field("description")
    private String description;

    @Field("created_by")
    private String createdBy;

    @Field("last_edited_by")
    private String lastEditedBy;

    @Field("metadata")
    private Map<String, Object> metadata;

    @Field("connector_id")
    @Indexed
    private Integer connectorMappingId;

    @JsonIgnore
    @LastModifiedDate
    @Field("last_updated_time")
    private Date lastUpdatedTime;

    /**
     * Nested flow structure
     */
    @Data
    public static class ConnectorFlow implements Serializable {
        private static final long serialVersionUID = 7001684943459256336L;

        @Field("nodes")
        private List<Map<String, Object>> nodes;

        @Field("edges")
        private List<Map<String, Object>> edges;

        @Field("metadata")
        private Map<String, Object> metadata;
    }

    @Field("connector_flow")
    private ConnectorFlow connectorFlow;

}

Key Points

  • MongoDB field names snake_case (flow_id, created_by, connector_flow, etc.).

  • Java fields camelCase (flowId, createdBy, connectorFlow).

  • Keeps your Java code idiomatic (works with Lombok getters/setters).

  • Keeps Mongo queries simple:

    js
    db.connector_flow_data.find({ "connector_flow.nodes.data.community_id": "abc123" })

2. Service Layer

java
package com.italent.iconnector.xcommunitymongo.service;

import com.italent.iconnector.xcommunitymongo.model.ConnectorFlowData;
import com.italent.iconnector.xcommunitymongo.repository.ConnectorFlowDataRepository;
import org.springframework.stereotype.Service;

import java.util.List;
import java.util.Optional;

@Service
public class ConnectorFlowDataService {

    private final ConnectorFlowDataRepository repository;

    public ConnectorFlowDataService(ConnectorFlowDataRepository repository) {
        this.repository = repository;
    }

    // Create or Update
    public ConnectorFlowData saveFlow(ConnectorFlowData flowData) {
        return repository.save(flowData);
    }

    // Read (single)
    public Optional<ConnectorFlowData> getFlowById(String flowId) {
        return repository.findById(flowId);
    }

    // Read (all)
    public List<ConnectorFlowData> getAllFlows() {
        return repository.findAll();
    }

    // Delete
    public void deleteFlow(String flowId) {
        repository.deleteById(flowId);
    }
}

3. REST Controller (Expose to Frontend)

java
package com.italent.iconnector.xcommunitymongo.controller;

import com.italent.iconnector.xcommunitymongo.model.ConnectorFlowData;
import com.italent.iconnector.xcommunitymongo.service.ConnectorFlowDataService;
import org.springframework.http.ResponseEntity;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.*;

import java.util.List;

@RestController
@RequestMapping("/api/flows")
public class ConnectorFlowDataController {

    private final ConnectorFlowDataService service;

    public ConnectorFlowDataController(ConnectorFlowDataService service) {
        this.service = service;
    }

    // Create or Update
    @PostMapping
    public ResponseEntity<ConnectorFlowData> saveFlow(@RequestBody ConnectorFlowData flowData) {
        return ResponseEntity.ok(service.saveFlow(flowData));
    }

    // Get by ID
    @GetMapping("/{flowId}")
    public ResponseEntity<ConnectorFlowData> getFlow(@PathVariable String flowId) {
        return service.getFlowById(flowId)
                .map(ResponseEntity::ok)
                .orElse(ResponseEntity.notFound().build());
    }

    // Get all
    @GetMapping
    public List<ConnectorFlowData> getAllFlows() {
        return service.getAllFlows();
    }

    // Delete
    @DeleteMapping("/{flowId}")
    public ResponseEntity<Void> deleteFlow(@PathVariable String flowId) {
        service.deleteFlow(flowId);
        return ResponseEntity.noContent().build();
    }
}

package com.italent.iconnector.xcommunitymongo.model;

import java.io.Serializable;
import java.util.Date;
import java.util.List;
import java.util.Map;
import java.util.UUID;

import org.springframework.data.annotation.Id;
import org.springframework.data.annotation.LastModifiedDate;
import org.springframework.data.mongodb.core.index.Indexed;
import org.springframework.data.mongodb.core.mapping.Document;
import org.springframework.data.mongodb.core.mapping.Field;

import com.fasterxml.jackson.annotation.JsonIgnoreProperties;

import lombok.Data;

@Document(collection = "react_flow_data")
@JsonIgnoreProperties(ignoreUnknown = true)
@Data
public class ReactFlowData implements Serializable {

    private static final long serialVersionUID = 1L;

    @Id
    @Field("flow_id")
    private String flowId = UUID.randomUUID().toString();

    @Field("name")
    @Indexed
    private String name;

    @Field("description")
    private String description;

    @Field("created_by")
    private String createdBy;

    @Field("last_edited_by")
    private String lastEditedBy;

    @Field("metadata")
    private Map<String, Object> metadata;

    @LastModifiedDate
    @Field("last_updated_time")
    private Date lastUpdatedTime;

    /**
     * Nested React Flow structure
     */
    @Data
    public static class ReactFlow implements Serializable {
        private static final long serialVersionUID = 1L;

        @Field("nodes")
        private List<Map<String, Object>> nodes;

        @Field("edges")
        private List<Map<String, Object>> edges;

        @Field("metadata")
        private Map<String, Object> metadata;
    }

    @Field("react_flow")
    private ReactFlow reactFlow;
}

Updated Model

java
package com.italent.iconnector.xcommunitymongo.model;

import java.io.Serializable;
import java.util.Date;
import java.util.List;
import java.util.Map;
import java.util.UUID;

import org.springframework.data.annotation.Id;
import org.springframework.data.annotation.LastModifiedDate;
import org.springframework.data.mongodb.core.index.Indexed;
import org.springframework.data.mongodb.core.mapping.Document;
import org.springframework.data.mongodb.core.mapping.Field;

import com.fasterxml.jackson.annotation.JsonIgnoreProperties;

import lombok.Data;

@Document(collection = "flow_data")
@JsonIgnoreProperties(ignoreUnknown = true)
@Data
public class FlowData implements Serializable {

    private static final long serialVersionUID = 1L;

    @Id
    @Field("flow_id")
    private String flowId = UUID.randomUUID().toString();

    @Field("name")
    @Indexed
    private String name;

    @Field("description")
    private String description;

    @Field("created_by")
    private String createdBy;

    @Field("last_edited_by")
    private String lastEditedBy;

    @Field("metadata")
    private Map<String, Object> metadata;

    @LastModifiedDate
    @Field("last_updated_time")
    private Date lastUpdatedTime;

    /**
     * Nested flow structure
     */
    @Data
    public static class Flow implements Serializable {
        private static final long serialVersionUID = 1L;

        @Field("nodes")
        private List<Map<String, Object>> nodes;

        @Field("edges")
        private List<Map<String, Object>> edges;

        @Field("metadata")
        private Map<String, Object> metadata;
    }

    @Field("flow")
    private Flow flow;
}

import com.italent.iconnector.xcommunitymongo.model.FlowData;
import com.italent.iconnector.xcommunitymongo.service.FlowDataService;
import org.springframework.http.ResponseEntity;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.*;

import java.util.List;

@RestController
@RequestMapping("/api/flows")
public class FlowDataController {

    private final FlowDataService service;

    public FlowDataController(FlowDataService service) {
        this.service = service;
    }

    @PostMapping
    public ResponseEntity<FlowData> saveFlow(@RequestBody FlowData flowData) {
        return ResponseEntity.ok(service.saveFlow(flowData));
    }

    @GetMapping("/{flowId}")
    public ResponseEntity<FlowData> getFlow(@PathVariable String flowId) {
        return service.getFlowById(flowId)
                .map(ResponseEntity::ok)
                .orElse(ResponseEntity.notFound().build());
    }

    @GetMapping
    public List<FlowData> getAllFlows() {
        return service.getAllFlows();
    }

    @DeleteMapping("/{flowId}")
    public ResponseEntity<Void> deleteFlow(@PathVariable String flowId) {
        service.deleteFlow(flowId);
        return ResponseEntity.noContent().build();
    }
}

1. Drag-and-Drop in React Flow

React Flow supports dragging nodes onto the canvas from a sidebar (or creating them programmatically).

Example Setup

tsx
import React, { useCallback } from "react";
import ReactFlow, {
  addEdge,
  Background,
  Controls,
  useNodesState,
  useEdgesState,
} from "reactflow";
import "reactflow/dist/style.css";

const initialNodes = [];
const initialEdges = [];

export default function FlowEditor() {
  const [nodes, setNodes, onNodesChange] = useNodesState(initialNodes);
  const [edges, setEdges, onEdgesChange] = useEdgesState(initialEdges);

  const onConnect = useCallback(
    (params: any) => setEdges((eds) => addEdge(params, eds)),
    []
  );

  // Handle drop from sidebar
  const onDrop = useCallback(
    (event: React.DragEvent) => {
      event.preventDefault();

      const type = event.dataTransfer.getData("application/reactflow");
      if (!type) return;

      const position = { x: event.clientX - 200, y: event.clientY - 80 };

      const newNode = {
        id: `${+new Date()}`,
        type,
        position,
        data: { label: `${type} node` },
      };

      setNodes((nds) => nds.concat(newNode));
    },
    [setNodes]
  );

  const onDragOver = useCallback((event: React.DragEvent) => {
    event.preventDefault();
    event.dataTransfer.dropEffect = "move";
  }, []);

  return (
    <div className="w-full h-screen flex">
      {/* Sidebar for dragging nodes */}
      <aside className="w-1/5 bg-gray-200 p-4">
        <div
          className="p-2 bg-white rounded shadow cursor-move"
          onDragStart={(event) =>
            event.dataTransfer.setData("application/reactflow", "default")
          }
          draggable
        >
          Default Node
        </div>
        <div
          className="p-2 bg-white rounded shadow cursor-move mt-2"
          onDragStart={(event) =>
            event.dataTransfer.setData("application/reactflow", "special")
          }
          draggable
        >
          Special Node
        </div>
      </aside>

      {/* React Flow Canvas */}
      <div className="flex-1" onDrop={onDrop} onDragOver={onDragOver}>
        <ReactFlow
          nodes={nodes}
          edges={edges}
          onNodesChange={onNodesChange}
          onEdgesChange={onEdgesChange}
          onConnect={onConnect}
          fitView
        >
          <Background />
          <Controls />
        </ReactFlow>
      </div>
    </div>
  );
}

2. Save & Load from MongoDB

  • When the user finishes editing, you can send the React Flow state to your Spring Boot backend:

tsx
const saveFlow = async () => {
  const flow = { nodes, edges, metadata: { zoom: 1 } };

  await fetch("/api/flows", {
    method: "POST",
    headers: { "Content-Type": "application/json" },
    body: JSON.stringify({
      name: "My Flow",
      description: "Drag-and-drop test",
      createdBy: "user123",
      flow: flow,
    }),
  });
};

  • On load, fetch from /api/flows/{id} and set into React Flow:

tsx
useEffect(() => {
  fetch("/api/flows/123")
    .then((res) => res.json())
    .then((data) => {
      setNodes(data.flow.nodes || []);
      setEdges(data.flow.edges || []);
    });
}, []);

diff bet weeen @rest controller vs @controller when these are introduced
ChatGPT said:

Great question This is one of the most asked interview / practical differences in Spring MVC vs Spring Boot. Let me break it down clearly:

@Controller

  • Introduced in: Spring 2.5 (2007).

  • Purpose: Marks a class as a Spring MVC controller.

  • Default behavior:

    • Returns views (HTML, JSP, Thymeleaf templates, etc.), not JSON.

    • If you return a String Spring assumes its a view name, not a raw response body.

  • To return JSON/XML you must also annotate methods with @ResponseBody.

Example:

java
@Controller
@RequestMapping("/hello")
public class HelloController {

    @GetMapping
    @ResponseBody  // Required if you want JSON response
    public String sayHello() {
        return "Hello World";  // returns JSON/text response
    }

    @GetMapping("/view")
    public String helloPage() {
        return "hello";  // resolves to hello.html or hello.jsp
    }
}

@RestController

  • Introduced in: Spring 4 (2013).

  • Purpose: Specialized version of @Controller for REST APIs.

  • Default behavior:

    • Adds @ResponseBody implicitly to every method.

    • Methods return JSON/XML directly, not views.

  • Designed for microservices / APIs (Spring Boot style).

Example:

java
@RestController
@RequestMapping("/api/hello")
public class HelloRestController {

    @GetMapping
    public String sayHello() {
        return "Hello World";  // returns JSON/text response
    }
}

(no need for @ResponseBody).

Quick Comparison

Aspect@Controller@RestController
Introduced inSpring 2.5Spring 4
Primary useMVC (returning views)REST APIs (returning JSON/XML)
Default returnView name (e.g., index.html)JSON/XML response body
@ResponseBodyRequired to return JSON/XMLImplicit (auto-applied)
Use caseTraditional web apps (JSP, Thymeleaf, etc)APIs / Microservices (Spring Boot apps)

Rule of thumb:

  • Use @Controller if youre building server-side rendered pages (JSP, Thymeleaf).

  • Use @RestController if youre building APIs (JSON/XML) for frontend apps like React, Angular, or mobile apps.

Perfect Lets dig into how Spring internally implements @RestController.

How @RestController is defined

If you open Springs source code (Spring Web MVC), youll see:

java
@Target(value=TYPE)
@Retention(value=RUNTIME)
@Documented
@Controller
@ResponseBody
public @interface RestController {
}

What this means

  • @RestController is literally just @Controller + @ResponseBody.

  • Because of @ResponseBody, every method in the class automatically returns the object as the HTTP response body, instead of resolving a view.

  • The object is serialized using HttpMessageConverters (e.g., to JSON with Jackson, XML with JAXB).

Example Side by Side

Without @RestController

java
@Controller
@RequestMapping("/api")
public class UserController {

    @GetMapping("/user")
    @ResponseBody   // needed here
    public User getUser() {
        return new User("John", "Doe");
    }
}

With @RestController

java
@RestController
@RequestMapping("/api")
public class UserRestController {

    @GetMapping("/user")
    public User getUser() {   // @ResponseBody is auto applied
        return new User("John", "Doe");
    }
}

Both endpoints behave exactly the same they return JSON.
Difference: with @RestController, you dont need to repeat @ResponseBody on every method.

Summary

  • @Controller returns views by default.

  • @RestController = @Controller + @ResponseBody.

  • Saves boilerplate for REST APIs by auto-applying @ResponseBody at class level.

ChatGPT said:

Got it Youre asking:

What if I use @RestController but want to return a view (HTML, JSP, Thymeleaf) instead of JSON?

Important Rule

  • @Controller returns views (unless you add @ResponseBody).

  • @RestController always returns the response body (JSON/XML/text).

    • It cannot return a view name directly.

Correct Way to Return a View

Use @Controller, not @RestController.

Example with Thymeleaf

java
@Controller
@RequestMapping("/pages")
public class PageController {

    @GetMapping("/home")
    public String homePage(Model model) {
        model.addAttribute("message", "Welcome to Home Page");
        return "home";   // resolves to home.html (Thymeleaf template)
    }
}

  • Returns home.html (located under src/main/resources/templates/home.html if using Spring Boot + Thymeleaf).

  • Springs ViewResolver maps "home" actual template.

Why @RestController Doesnt Work Here

java
@RestController
public class PageRestController {

    @GetMapping("/home")
    public String homePage() {
        return "home";  //  returns the string "home" as plain text, NOT a view
    }
}

With @RestController, "home" will be sent as HTTP response body, not as a view name.

Workarounds if You Must Use @RestController

  1. Return ModelAndView:

    java
    @RestController
public class PageRestController {

    @GetMapping("/dashboard")
    public ModelAndView dashboard() {
        ModelAndView mv = new ModelAndView("dashboard");
        mv.addObject("user", "John Doe");
        return mv;
    }
}

    Works, but goes against the purpose of @RestController.

  2. Better Approach:
    Use @Controller for pages (views) and @RestController for APIs.
    Keep them separate for clarity.

Best practice:

  • Use @Controller when you need to return views (JSP, Thymeleaf, Freemarker, etc.).

  • Use @RestController when you need to return JSON/XML (for APIs).

ChatGPT said:

Ah, that error explains everything 

arduino
No static resource hello/home.
org.springframework.web.servlet.resource.NoResourceFoundException

This happens because Spring is not finding a view template for "hello/home".

Why This Happens

  1. You used @Controller and returned "hello/home" as a view name.

  2. Spring Boots ViewResolver is looking for a template file at:

  • src/main/resources/templates/hello/home.html (for Thymeleaf/Freemarker)

  • or src/main/webapp/WEB-INF/jsp/hello/home.jsp (for JSP)

  1. Since it doesnt exist, Spring assumes its a static resource tries to load /hello/home from src/main/resources/static fails.

Fix: Place the View Template Correctly

If using Thymeleaf (default in Spring Boot)

  • Create file:

    css
    src/main/resources/templates/hello/home.html

  • Example home.html:

    html
    <!DOCTYPE html>
<html xmlns:th="http://www.thymeleaf.org">
<head>
    <title>Hello Page</title>
</head>
<body>
    <h1 th:text="${message}">Hello!</h1>
</body>
</html>

  • Controller:

    java
    @Controller
public class HelloController {

    @GetMapping("/hello/home")
    public String helloHome(Model model) {
        model.addAttribute("message", "Welcome Home!");
        return "hello/home";  // resolves to templates/hello/home.html
    }
}

If using JSP

  • Add dependency in pom.xml:

    xml
    <dependency>
    <groupId>org.apache.tomcat.embed</groupId>
    <artifactId>tomcat-embed-jasper</artifactId>
</dependency>
<dependency>
    <groupId>javax.servlet</groupId>
    <artifactId>jstl</artifactId>
</dependency>

  • Place JSP file at:

    swift
    src/main/webapp/WEB-INF/jsp/hello/home.jsp

  • Example home.jsp:

    jsp
    <html>
<body>
    <h1>${message}</h1>
</body>
</html>

  • Add config in application.properties:

    properties
    spring.mvc.view.prefix=/WEB-INF/jsp/
spring.mvc.view.suffix=.jsp

Key Point

  • Templates (Thymeleaf, JSP, etc.) go in templates/ or WEB-INF/jsp/.

  • Static files (CSS, JS, images) go in static/.

Thats why Spring complained it was looking in static/ because it couldnt resolve a template.
